{{short description|An underwater exploration and recovery vehicle that moves about on the bottom with wheels or tracks}}
{{Unreferenced|auto=yes|date=December 2009}}
[[File:Flexjet.jpg|thumb]]
A '''bottom crawler''' is an [[underwater]] exploration and recovery vehicle. It is designed to sink to the bottom of a body of water, where it moves about using traction against the bottom with [[wheel]]s or [[Continuous track|tracks]]. It is usually tethered to a surface ship by cables providing power, control, video, and lifting capabilities, but this is not essential.

Such devices have been proposed for use in recovering deep seabed minerals, such as [[manganese nodules]].

These also have been considered since the late 1960s for use in offshore [[oil exploration]] and production in extremely deep water, but practical devices have used other technologies from the sea surface, such as moored barges and [[tension leg platform]]s.

