'''Drue Leyton''' (12 July 1903 - 8 February 1997) was an American actress and member of the [[French resistance]]. She was born '''Dorothy Elizabeth Blackman''' in [[Somers, Wisconsin]]. She became an actress after a failed mariage and notably acted in [[Green Grow the Lilacs (play)|Green Grow the Lilacs]] on Broadway and several [[Charlie Chan]] films.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/name/nm0508100/bio|title=Drue Leyton|website=IMDb|access-date=2017-06-08}}</ref> In 1937 Leyton moved to Paris with her future husband [[:fr:Jacques Terrane|Jacques Terrane]] a Franco-American actor who died in [[Syria]] in 1941 fighting with the [[Free France|Free French forces]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://collections.ushmm.org/findingaids/1988.93_01_fnd_en.pdf|title=TARTIÈRE FAMILY PAPERS, 1920‐1950|last=|first=|date=|website=United States Holocaust Memorial Museum Archives|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=8 June 2017}}</ref>
Leyton broadcast for the [[Voice of America]] whilst acting in Paris in 1938 and her criticisms of the Nazi regime during these broadcasts earned her a promise of execution announced by Berlin radio.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.livresdeguerre.net/forum/contribution.php?index=53126&surl=AD|title=La comtesse vue par une Américaine, commentatrice radiophonique en France - Histomag 39-45 - forum "Livres de guerre"|last=Ghémard|first=Jacques|website=www.livresdeguerre.net|access-date=2017-06-08}}</ref> She was arrested by the Nazis when France became [[German military administration in occupied France during World War II|occupied by the German military]] but managed to escape from her prison camp with the help of French doctors by feigning cancer. She returned to her home in [[Barbizon]] in 1942 and joined the resistance movement helping 42 downed allied airmen escape to freedom and hid others in her home until the war ended. During this period she was known as '''Dorothy Tartière''' which was the real name of her husband.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.fr/books?id=IHN2DgAAQBAJ&lpg=PA334&dq=Dorothy%20Tartiere&hl=fr&pg=PA334#v=onepage&q=Dorothy%20Tartiere&f=false|title=They came from Burgundy: A study of the Bourgogne escape line|last=Janes|first=Keith|date=2017-03-28|publisher=Troubador Publishing Ltd|isbn=9781788036474|language=en}}</ref> She wrote about this period in a book ''The House Near Paris.''<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.unz.org/Pub/SaturdayRev-1946mar16-00012|title="Lady Who Took Chances" by Theodore M. Purdy, The Saturday Review, Saturday, March 16th, 1946|website=UNZ.org|access-date=2017-06-08}}</ref>
