{{about|the type of wetland|other uses|Fen (disambiguation)}}
{{distinguish|Fenn}}
[[File:Avaste soo ääreala (5).JPG|thumb|Outer [[Avaste_Nature_Reserve|Avaste Fen]], western [[Estonia]]]]
[[File:Illustrated diagram of a fen.jpg|thumb]]
A '''fen''' is one of the main types of [[wetland]], the others being grassy [[marsh]]es, forested [[swamp]]s, and peaty [[bog]]s. Along with bogs, fens are a kind of [[mire]]. Fens are [[minerotrophic]] [[peatland]]s,<ref>Rydin, Hakan and John K. Jeglum. ''The Biology of Peatlands'', 2nd edn. Oxford: OUP, 2013. p. 11. {{ISBN|978-0-19-960299-5}}.</ref> usually fed by mineral-rich surface water or [[groundwater]].<ref>[[#Godwin|Godwin ''et al.'' (2002)]].</ref> They are characterised by their distinct water chemistry, which is [[pH|pH neutral]] or [[alkali]]ne, with relatively high dissolved [[mineral]] levels but few other [[plant nutrition|plant nutrient]]s. They are usually dominated by grasses and [[sedge]]s, and typically have brown mosses in general including ''[[Scorpidium]]'' or ''[[Drepanocladus]]''.<ref name="Keddy_8">[[#Keddy|Keddy (2010)]], p.&nbsp;8.</ref> Fens frequently have a high diversity of other plant species including carnivorous plants such as ''[[Pinguicula]]''.<ref>[[#Wheeler|Wheeler & Giller (1982)]]</ref><ref>[[#Keddy|Keddy (2010)]], Chapter 9.</ref> They may also occur along large lakes and rivers where seasonal changes in water level maintain wet soils with few woody plants.<ref>[[#Charlton|Charlton & Hilts (1989)]]</ref> The distribution of individual species of fen plants is often closely connected to water regimes and nutrient concentrations.<ref>[[#Slack|Slack ''et al.'' (1980)]]</ref><ref>[[#Schröder|Schröder ''et al.'' (2005)]]</ref>

Fens have a characteristic set of plant species, which sometimes provide the best indicators of environmental conditions. For example, fen indicator species in New York State include ''[[Carex|Carex flava]]'', ''[[Cladium mariscoides]]'', ''[[Potentilla fruticosa]]'', ''[[Pogonia ophioglossoides]]'' and ''[[Parnassia glauca]]''.<ref>[[#Godwin|Godwin ''et al.'' (2002)]], Table 3.</ref>

Fens are distinguished from [[bog]]s, which are [[acid]]ic, low in minerals, and usually dominated by sedges and shrubs, along with abundant mosses in the genus ''[[Sphagnum]]''.<ref name="Keddy_8"/>  Bogs also tend to exist on dome-shaped landmasses where they receive almost all of their usually-abundant moisture from rainfall, whereas fens appear on slopes, flats, or depressions and are fed by surface and underground water in addition to rain.

Fens have been damaged in the past by land drainage, and also by [[peat]] cutting.<ref>[[#Sheail|Sheail & Wells (1983)]]</ref> Some are now being carefully restored with modern management methods.<ref>[[#Keddy|Keddy (2010)]], Chapter 13.</ref> The principal challenges are to restore natural water flow regimes, to maintain the quality of water, and to prevent invasion by woody plants.

==Vegetation==

''[[Carr (topography)|Carr]]'' is the northern European equivalent of the wooded [[swamp]] of the [[southeastern United States]],<ref>[http://www.buglife.org.uk/conservation/adviceonmanagingbaphabitats/fens Bug Life] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100304033143/http://www.buglife.org.uk/conservation/adviceonmanagingbaphabitats/fens |date=2010-03-04 }}</ref> also known in the United Kingdom as [[wet woodland]]. It is a fen overgrown with generally small trees of species such as [[willow]] (''Salix spp.'') or [[alder]] (''Alnus'' spp.). In general, fens may change in composition as [[peat]] accumulates. A list of species found in a fen can therefore cover a range of species from those remaining from the earlier stage in the [[Ecological succession|successional development]] to the [[Pioneer species|pioneers]] of the succeeding stage.

Where streams of base-rich water run through bog, these are often lined by strips of fen, separating "islands" of rain-fed bog.{{citation needed|date=September 2015}}

Temporary flooding by [[beaver]]s can have negative effects on fens.<ref>[[#Reddoch|Reddoch & Reddoch (2005)]]</ref>

==Use of term in literature==
Shakespeare used the term "fen-sucked" to describe the fog (literally: rising from marshes) in ''[[King Lear]]'', when Lear says "Infect her beauty, You fen-sucked fogs drawn by the powerful sun, To fall and blister."<ref>{{cite web|author1=William Shakespeare|title=King Lear, Act II, Scene IV, line 162|url=http://www.shakespeareswords.com/Plays.aspx?Ac=2&SC=4&IdPlay=11#153271|publisher=Penguin Books |accessdate=5 September 2015 |date=2008|quote=You nimble lightnings, dart your blinding flames, Into her scornful eyes! Infect her beauty, You fen-sucked fogs drawn by the powerful sun, To fall and blister.}}</ref>

