'''Geosmin''' is an [[organic compound]] with a distinct earthy flavor and aroma produced by certain bacteria, and is responsible for the earthy taste of [[beet]]s and a contributor to the strong scent ([[petrichor]]) that occurs in the air when rain falls after a dry spell of weather or when soil is disturbed.<ref>[http://www.expasy.org/spotlight/back_issues/035/ The earth's perfume], ''Protein Spotlight'', Issue 35, June 2003.</ref> In chemical terms, it is a [[Bicyclic molecule|bicyclic]] [[alcohol]] with [[chemical formula|formula]] {{Chemical formula|C|12|H|22|O}}, a derivative of [[decalin]]. Its name is derived from the Greek {{lang|el|γεω-}} "earth" and {{lang|el|ὀσμή}} "smell".

== Production ==

Geosmin is produced by the [[Gram-positive bacteria|gram-positive]] [[bacteria]] ''[[Streptomyces]]'' and various [[cyanobacteria]], and released when these [[microorganism]]s die.<ref>{{cite journal | authors = Izaguirre G, Taylor WD. | year = 2004 | title = A guide to geosmin- and MIB-producing cyanobacteria in the United States | journal = Water Sci Technol. | volume = 49 | issue = 9 | pages = 19–24 | pmid = 15237602}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | authors = Zaitlin B, Watson SB. | year = 2006 | title = Actinomycetes in relation to taste and odour in drinking water: Myths, tenets and truths | journal = Water Res. | volume = 40 | issue = 9 | pages = 1741–53 | pmid = 16600325 | doi = 10.1016/j.watres.2006.02.024}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | authors = Suurnäkki S, Gomez-Saez GV, Rantala-Ylinen A, Jokela J, Fewer DP, Sivonen K. | year = 2015 | title = Identification of geosmin and 2-methylisoborneol in cyanobacteria and molecular detection methods for the producers of these compounds | journal = Water Res. | volume = 68 | issue = 1 | pages = 56–66 | pmid = 25462716 | doi = 10.1016/j.watres.2014.09.037}}</ref> Communities whose [[water]] supplies depend on surface water can periodically experience episodes of unpleasant-tasting water when a sharp drop in the population of these bacteria releases geosmin into the local water supply. Under [[acid]]ic conditions, geosmin decomposes into odorless substances.<ref>{{cite journal | pmid = 5866039 | volume=13 | issue=6 |date=November 1965 | pages=935–8 | last1 = Gerber | first1 = NN | last2 = Lechevalier | first2 = HA | title = Geosmin, an earthly-smelling substance isolated from actinomycetes. | pmc = 1058374 | journal = Applied Microbiology}}</ref>

In 2006, the [[biosynthesis]] of geosmin by a bifunctional ''[[Streptomyces coelicolor]]'' [[enzyme]] was unveiled.<ref>{{Cite journal | doi = 10.1021/ja062669x | volume = 128 | issue = 25 | pages = 8128–8129 | last1 = Jiang | first1 = J. | first2 = X. | last2 = He | first3 = D.E. | last3 = Cane | title = Geosmin biosynthesis. ''Streptomyces coelicolor'' germacradienol/germacrene D Synthase converts farnesyl diphosphate to geosmin | journal = [[J. Am. Chem. Soc.]] | year = 2006 | pmid = 16787064}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal | doi = 10.1038/nchembio.2007.29 | volume = 3| last1 = Jiang | first1 = J. | first2 = X. | last2 = He | first3 = D.E. | last3 = Cane | pmc = 3013058 | title = Biosynthesis of the earthy odorant geosmin by a bifunctional ''Streptomyces coelicolor'' enzyme | journal = [[Nat. Chem. Biol.]] | year = 2007 | pages = 711–5 | pmid = 17873868 | issue = 11}}</ref> A single enzyme, [[geosmin synthase]], converts [[farnesyl diphosphate]] to geosmin in a two-step reaction.

''Streptomyces coelicolor'' is the model representative of a group of soil-dwelling bacteria with a complex lifecycle involving [[Mycelium|mycelial growth]] and [[spore formation]]. Besides the production of volatile geosmin, it also produces many other complex molecules of pharmacological interest; its [[genome]] sequence is available at the [[Sanger Institute]].<ref name="Sanger">{{cite web |title=The genome of ''Streptomyces coelicolor'' A3(2) producing geosmin |publisher=Sanger Institute |url=http://www.sanger.ac.uk/Projects/S_coelicolor/ |accessdate=2009-01-31}}</ref>

== Effects ==

The [[human nose]] is extremely sensitive to geosmin and is able to detect it at concentrations as low as 5 parts per trillion.<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Polak | first1 = E.H. | last2 = Provasi | first2 = J. | title = Odor sensitivity to geosmin enantiomers | journal = Chemical Senses | volume = 17 | pages = 23 | year = 1992 | doi = 10.1093/chemse/17.1.23 }}</ref>

Geosmin is responsible for the muddy smell in many commercially important freshwater fish such as [[carp]] and [[catfish]].<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Vallod|first=D.|last2=Cravedi|first2=J. P.|last3=Hillenweck|first3=A.|last4=Robin|first4=J.|date=2007-04-03|title=Analysis of the off-flavor risk in carp production in ponds in Dombes and Forez (France)|url=https://link.springer.com/article/10.1007/s10499-007-9080-7|journal=Aquaculture International|language=en|volume=15|issue=3-4|pages=287–298|doi=10.1007/s10499-007-9080-7|issn=0967-6120}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Lovell|first=Richard T.|last2=Lelana|first2=Iwan Y.|last3=Boyd|first3=Claude E.|last4=Armstrong|first4=Martin S.|date=1986-05-01|title=Geosmin and Musty-Muddy Flavors in Pond-Raised Channel Catfish|url=https://dx.doi.org/10.1577/1548-8659(1986)1152.0.CO;2|journal=Transactions of the American Fisheries Society|volume=115|issue=3|pages=485–489|doi=10.1577/1548-8659(1986)115<485:gamfip>2.0.co;2|issn=0002-8487}}</ref> Geosmin combines with [[2-methylisoborneol]], which concentrates in the fatty skin and dark muscle tissues. Geosmin breaks down in acid conditions; hence, vinegar and other acidic ingredients are used in fish recipes to help reduce the muddy flavor.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=3tKAfqxkFAIC|title=Westwood Lake Chronicles|last=Winkler|first=Lawrence|date=2012-08-06|publisher=Lawrence Winkler|isbn=9780991694105|language=en}}</ref>

